## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

# Count the number of zeros in the dataset for numeric columns
zero_count_before <- sapply(bc, function(x) if (is.numeric(x)) sum(x == 0, na.rm = TRUE) else NA)

# This replaces zeros with mean values for numeric columns
bc_mean_imputed <- bc %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~replace(.x, .x == 0, mean(.x[.x != 0], na.rm = TRUE))))

# This counts the number of zeros again to confirm they have been replaced
zero_count_after <- sapply(bc_mean_imputed, function(x) if (is.numeric(x)) sum(x == 0, na.rm = TRUE) else NA)

# Print the counts before and after mean imputation
print(list("Before" = zero_count_before, "After" = zero_count_after))

# 2.2.3. SKEWNESS: YEO-JOHNSON TRANSFORMATION

library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':

library(bestNormalize)
## Warning: package 'bestNormalize' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(tibble)

# List of variables to remove based on the previous correlation analysis
numeric_columns <- c("concave_points_worst", "perimeter_worst", "concave_points_mean",
                     "radius_worst", "perimeter_mean", "area_worst", "radius_mean",
                     "area_mean", "concavity_mean", "concavity_worst", "area_se",
                     "radius_se", "perimeter_se", "compactness_mean", "compactness_worst")

bc_yeojohnson_transformed <- bc_cleaned

# Apply the Yeo-Johnson transformation to each numeric variable
for (var in numeric_columns) {
    transformation_result <- bestNormalize(bc_cleaned[[var]], family = "yeojohnson")
    bc_yeojohnson_transformed[[var]] <- transformation_result$x.t
}

# Generate individual plots for each variable
create_plots <- function(data_frame, variables) {
    plots_list <- list()
    for (var in variables) {
        data_original <- data.frame(Value = data_frame[[var]])
        data_transformed <- data_frame(Value = bc_yeojohnson_transformed[[var]])
  
        p1 <- ggplot(data_original, aes(x = Value)) +
            geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "skyblue", color = "black") +
            ggtitle(paste("Original -", var))
  
        p2 <- ggplot(data_transformed, aes(x = Value)) +
            geom_histogram(bins = 30, fill = "lightgreen", color = "black") +
            ggtitle(paste("Yeo-Johnson Transformed -", var))
  
        # Combine the plots for each variable into a list
        plots_list[[var]] <- list(p1, p2)
    }
    
    # Flatten the list of lists into a single list of plots
    plots_flat <- do.call(c, plots_list)
    
    # Arrange the plots in a grid
    grid.arrange(grobs = plots_flat, ncol = 2)
}

# Now call the create_plots function for sets of 5 variables
create_plots(bc_cleaned, numeric_columns[1:5])

4.0. RESULTS AND DISCUSSION 4.1. CONFUSION MATRIX

# 4.1.1.    CONFUSION MATRIX FOR DECISION TREE

library(caret)

# Make sure that the factor levels are in the same order
test_set$Diagnosis <- factor(test_set$Diagnosis, levels = c("Class1", "Class0"))

# Generate predictions using the tuned model
test_set_probs_tuned <- predict(tree_model_tuned, newdata = test_set, type = "prob")
test_set_predictions_tuned <- test_set_probs_tuned[, "Class1"]

# Convert probability predictions to binary class labels based on a threshold (e.g., 0.5)
# Here 'Class1' is considered as the positive case, so it is placed first in the factor levels
predictions_binary_tuned <- ifelse(test_set_predictions_tuned > 0.5, "Class1", "Class0")
predictions_factor_tuned <- factor(predictions_binary_tuned, levels = c("Class1", "Class0"))

# Create the confusion matrix using the binary predictions and actual labels
# The positive class should be 'Class1' (Malignant)
confusion_matrix_tuned <- confusionMatrix(predictions_factor_tuned, test_set$Diagnosis, positive = "Class1")

# Print the confusion matrix
print(confusion_matrix_tuned)

# 4.1.2. CONFUSION MATRIX FOR RANDOM FOREST

library(caret)
library(randomForest)

# Make sure that the factor levels are in the same order
test_set$Diagnosis <- factor(test_set$Diagnosis, levels = c("Class1", "Class0"))

# Generate predictions using the Random Forest model
test_set_probs_rf <- predict(rf_model, newdata = test_set, type = "prob")
test_set_predictions_rf <- test_set_probs_rf[, "Class1"]

# Convert probability predictions to binary class labels based on a threshold (e.g., 0.5)
# Here 'Class1' is considered as the positive case, so it is placed first in the factor levels
predictions_binary_rf <- ifelse(test_set_predictions_rf > 0.5, "Class1", "Class0")
predictions_factor_rf <- factor(predictions_binary_rf, levels = c("Class1", "Class0"))

# Create the confusion matrix using the binary predictions and actual labels
# The positive class should be 'Class1' (Malignant)
confusion_matrix_rf <- confusionMatrix(predictions_factor_rf, test_set$Diagnosis, positive = "Class1")

# Print the confusion matrix 
print(confusion_matrix_rf)

4.2. MODEL PERFORMANCE

# 4.2.1. ROC CURVE FOR TUNED DECISION TREE MODEL

library(ROCR)
## Warning: package 'ROCR' was built under R version 4.3.3
# Make sure the model generates class probabilities
test_set_probs <- predict(tree_model_tuned, newdata = test_set, type = "prob")
test_set_predictions <- test_set_probs[, "Class1"]

# Prepare the prediction object for ROCR
pred <- prediction(predictions = test_set_predictions, labels = test_set$Diagnosis)

# Calculate the performance of the ROC
perf <- performance(pred, "tpr", "fpr")

# Plot the ROC curve with a title
plot(perf, colorize = FALSE, col = "blue", main = "ROC Curve for Tuned Decision Tree Model")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "red")

# Calculate the area under the curve (AUC)
auc <- performance(pred, "auc")
auc_value <- auc@y.values[[1]]

# Print the AUC value on the plot
text(x = 0.6, y = 0.2, labels = paste("AUC:", round(auc_value, 4)), col = "red")

# Print the AUC value on the console
cat("AUC:", auc_value, "\n")
## AUC: 0.9572094

importance <- varImp(rf_model, scale = FALSE)
print(importance)

## concave_points_worst  21.226

## perimeter_worst       20.429

## perimeter_se           3.457
## ID                     2.459
# Convert the importance object to a data frame and add variable names as a new column.
importance_df <- as.data.frame(importance$importance)
importance_df$Variable <- rownames(importance_df)

# Remove any rows where the variable name is 'ID' to exclude it from the importance plot.
importance_df <- importance_df[importance_df$Variable != "ID", ]

# Plot the variable importance using ggplot2. Variables are ordered by importance for clarity.
ggplot(importance_df, aes(x = reorder(Variable, Overall), y = Overall)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    coord_flip() +  # Flips the axis to display variable names horizontally
    xlab("Variables") + 
    ylab("Importance") + 
ggtitle("Variable Importance in Random Forest Model")

# 4.3.2. PARTIAL DEPENDENCE PLOT FOR RANDOM FOREST

library(randomForest)
library(pdp)
## Warning: package 'pdp' was built under R version 4.3.3
library(ggplot2)

# Determine the most important variable from the random forest model
important_var <- varImp(rf_model, scale = FALSE)$importance %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% 
    slice_max(Overall) %>% 
    rownames()

# Generate partial dependence data for the most important variable using a specified grid resolution
pdp_data <- partial(rf_model, pred.var = important_var, grid.resolution = 10)

# Convert the partial dependence data to a data frame for plotting
pdp_df <- as.data.frame(pdp_data)

# Construct the partial dependence plot using ggplot2
pdp_plot <- ggplot(pdp_df, aes(x = .data[[names(pdp_df)[1]]], y = .data[[names(pdp_df)[2]]])) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(title = paste("Partial Dependence Plot for", important_var),
         x = important_var,
         y = "Partial Dependence")

# Print the output of the plot
print(pdp_plot)
